WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.520 --> 00:00:03.730
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.730 --> 00:00:06.990
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:10.770
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:10.770 --> 00:00:15.299
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:15.299 --> 00:00:16.299
of videos.

00:00:16.299 --> 00:00:18.040
Thanks for your help.

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:23.710
In this video we will cover configuration
management tools Ansible, Puppet, and Chef.

00:00:23.710 --> 00:00:29.450
They are exam topic 6.6, which says you must
be able to recognize the capabilities of configuration

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:30.940
management mechanisms.

00:00:30.940 --> 00:00:36.110
So, just like with the other automation topics
on the CCNA, you don’t have to actually

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:40.620
be able to use these tools yet, but Cisco
expects you to have a basic understanding

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.550
of their purpose and capabilities.

00:00:42.550 --> 00:00:46.790
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:46.790 --> 00:00:52.930
First I’ll introduce configuration management
tools, what they are and why we use them.

00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:57.600
Then I’ll introduce some of the characteristics
of the configuration management tools Ansible,

00:00:57.600 --> 00:00:59.950
Puppet, and Chef.

00:00:59.950 --> 00:01:04.290
So far I’ve introduced various automation
tools, and I just want to say that these are

00:01:04.290 --> 00:01:05.530
just tools.

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:09.799
They are suitable for some jobs, and not suitable
for others.

00:01:09.799 --> 00:01:13.829
Depending on the company you work for and
its size, they might use a lot of different

00:01:13.829 --> 00:01:18.520
automation tools, or just a few of them, or
none at all.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:22.840
Configuration management tools like these
three can be useful in any network, but especially

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:28.310
in medium to large networks with hundreds
or even thousands of devices.

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:32.579
And make sure to watch until the end of the
video for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:01:32.579 --> 00:01:38.719
Software’s ExSim, the best practice exams
for the CCNA.

00:01:38.719 --> 00:01:43.200
To understand one reason why configuration
management tools are useful, let me explain

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:47.070
the concept of configuration drift.

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:51.780
Configuration drift is when individual changes
made over time cause a device’s configuration

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:57.409
to deviate from the standard and correct configurations
as defined by the company.

00:01:57.409 --> 00:02:00.610
This is not a good thing, and should be avoided
wherever possible.

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:05.460
I mentioned this earlier in the course, but
each device in a network typically doesn’t

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:08.390
have a totally unique configuration.

00:02:08.390 --> 00:02:13.030
Although each device will have unique parts
of its configuration, for example IP addresses

00:02:13.030 --> 00:02:19.110
and its host name, most of a device’s configuration
is usually defined in standard templates designed

00:02:19.110 --> 00:02:23.460
by the network architects or engineers of
the company.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:28.330
For example, you can expect all of your routers
to have the same SNMP configurations, the

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:34.830
same Syslog configurations, the same AAA configurations
for logging in, one or two WAN interfaces,

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:37.940
one or two LAN interfaces, etc.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:42.130
Those all follow standard templates, with
just a few unique configurations for each

00:02:42.130 --> 00:02:43.420
device.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:48.990
But, as individual engineers make changes
to devices, for example to troubleshoot and

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:54.860
fix network issues, test configurations, etc,
the configuration of a device can drift away

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:56.510
from the standard.

00:02:56.510 --> 00:03:01.590
Often records of these individual changes
and their reasons aren’t kept, and this

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.430
can lead to issues in the future.

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:08.700
For example, it might be hard to tell if a
certain configuration is necessary when looking

00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:11.530
at it a few years later.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:15.680
The configuration management tools we’ll
look at today can help with this, but even

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:20.730
without automation tools like Ansible, it
is best to have standard configuration management

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:22.170
practices.

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:26.710
For example, something I did in the past was
when a change is made, save the config as

00:03:26.710 --> 00:03:29.380
a text file and place it in a shared folder.

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:36.450
In my case, a standard file naming system
hostname_year month day was used.

00:03:36.450 --> 00:03:40.750
Notice in the screenshot here we have three
different versions of R1’s config from three

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:45.340
different dates, and three versions of R2’s
config as well.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:50.600
This helps keep track of previous versions
of the config and see when changes were made.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:54.780
However there are flaws to this system, as
an engineer might simply forget to place the

00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:58.500
new config in the folder after making changes.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.730
In that case, which one should be considered
the correct config?

00:04:01.730 --> 00:04:06.780
And even if the configurations are properly
saved in a folder like this, it doesn’t

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:10.080
guarantee that the configurations actually
match the standard.

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:13.400
It just helps us keep track of different versions
of the config.

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:19.509
Plus, a manual approach is not very scalable
in networks with hundreds of devices.

00:04:19.509 --> 00:04:24.590
So, configuration management tools can of
course help us with the issues I just mentioned

00:04:24.590 --> 00:04:31.639
like preventing configuration drift, but they
can also assist us in configuration provisioning.

00:04:31.639 --> 00:04:36.570
Configuration provisioning refers to how configuration
changes are applied to devices.

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:42.490
This includes configuring new devices too,
so not just making changes to current devices.

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:47.419
As you know, traditionally configuration provisioning
is done by connecting to devices one-by-one

00:04:47.419 --> 00:04:51.210
via SSH, or console as well of course.

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:53.949
But this is not practical in large networks.

00:04:53.949 --> 00:04:59.219
It simply doesn’t scale well in networks
with hundreds or thousands of devices.

00:04:59.219 --> 00:05:03.289
Configuration management tools like Ansible,
Puppet, and Chef allow us to make changes

00:05:03.289 --> 00:05:08.300
to devices on a mass scale with a fraction
of the time and effort.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:12.879
Two essential components that you’ll find
in all of these tools are templates and variables.

00:05:12.879 --> 00:05:17.789
Here’s an example of a template, where values
aren’t given for things like the hostname,

00:05:17.789 --> 00:05:22.300
IP address, mask, OSPF process ID, and area.

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:27.689
Instead, we use a separate file specifying
the variables for a specific device, R1 in

00:05:27.689 --> 00:05:29.870
this case.

00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:35.960
Given a template and the appropriate variables,
a config is generated and sent to the device.

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:40.060
Of course, this is just a small snippet of
a configuration, but I think you can see how

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:44.539
easy it would be to generate the configuration
of many devices at once.

00:05:44.539 --> 00:05:49.470
All devices can share the template, and we
just need to specify some variables like hostnames,

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:52.120
IP addresses, etc.

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:55.770
Exactly how these templates and variables
are managed is different depending on the

00:05:55.770 --> 00:06:00.520
tool, but they all use a system like this.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:04.409
Okay now let me introduce configuration management
tools.

00:06:04.409 --> 00:06:08.740
These are network automation tools that facilitate
the centralized control of large numbers of

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:10.319
network devices.

00:06:10.319 --> 00:06:15.479
They can be useful in networks of any size,
but typically they’re used in larger networks.

00:06:15.479 --> 00:06:20.599
The options you need to be aware of for the
CCNA are Ansible, Puppet, and Chef.

00:06:20.599 --> 00:06:25.270
When it comes to managing network devices,
that’s also the order of their popularity.

00:06:25.270 --> 00:06:28.360
Ansible first, Puppet second, and Chef third.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:33.650
However, these tools weren’t originally
developed for the management of network devices.

00:06:33.650 --> 00:06:38.219
They were originally developed after the rise
of VMs, to enable server system admins to

00:06:38.219 --> 00:06:42.169
automate the process of creating, configuring,
and removing VMs.

00:06:42.169 --> 00:06:48.389
But these days they are also widely used to
manage network devices, especially Ansible.

00:06:48.389 --> 00:06:52.669
They can be used to perform tasks such as
generate configurations for new devices on

00:06:52.669 --> 00:06:54.629
a large scale.

00:06:54.629 --> 00:06:58.889
Using templates it’s very simple to generate
a new configuration for a new device, it’s

00:06:58.889 --> 00:07:01.619
just a bit of copy and paste.

00:07:01.619 --> 00:07:04.569
They can be used to perform configuration
changes on devices.

00:07:04.569 --> 00:07:10.439
It can be all devices in your network, or
a certain subset of devices, or just one device.

00:07:10.439 --> 00:07:15.290
You tell Ansible or Puppet or Chef which changes
you want to make on which devices, and it

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:18.279
does the rest of the work for you.

00:07:18.279 --> 00:07:22.409
These tools can also be used to check device
configurations for compliance with defined

00:07:22.409 --> 00:07:23.409
standards.

00:07:23.409 --> 00:07:28.439
If a device’s configuration doesn’t match
the standard, an alert could be sent out,

00:07:28.439 --> 00:07:29.610
for example.

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:33.490
Then you can investigate that issue and fix
it, to make the configuration comply with

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:35.069
the standard again.

00:07:35.069 --> 00:07:37.569
Or you can automate the change.

00:07:37.569 --> 00:07:41.969
You can also compare configurations between
devices, and between different versions of

00:07:41.969 --> 00:07:44.110
configurations on the same device.

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:48.080
These are just some examples of what you can
do with these tools.

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:52.619
Basically, they solve the problem of managing
the configurations of devices in networks

00:07:52.619 --> 00:07:55.090
with hundreds or thousands of different devices.

00:07:55.090 --> 00:08:02.099
Now let’s take a look at the basic characteristics
of each of these three tools.

00:08:02.099 --> 00:08:04.139
First up, Ansible.

00:08:04.139 --> 00:08:09.999
Ansible is a configuration management tool
owned by Red Hat, famous for Red Hat Linux.

00:08:09.999 --> 00:08:12.669
Ansible itself is written in Python.

00:08:12.669 --> 00:08:17.460
The other two I’ll introduce, Puppet and
Chef, are written in a different language,

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:18.569
Ruby.

00:08:18.569 --> 00:08:19.589
Ansible is agentless.

00:08:19.589 --> 00:08:21.159
So, what does that mean?

00:08:21.159 --> 00:08:26.330
It means that it doesn’t require any special
software to run on the managed devices.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:32.909
Instead, Ansible simply uses SSH to connect
to devices, make configuration changes, extract

00:08:32.909 --> 00:08:35.250
information, etc.

00:08:35.250 --> 00:08:39.560
This is a big advantage of Ansible which makes
it very versatile, and it’s probably the

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:45.100
reason that it is the most popular choice
for network device configuration management.

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:48.040
Ansible also uses what’s called a push model.

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:53.850
The Ansible server, also called the control
node, uses SSH to connect to managed devices

00:08:53.850 --> 00:08:57.040
and push configuration changes to them.

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:01.330
This is different than Puppet and Chef which
use a pull model, in which the managed devices

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:05.770
connect to the server to receive their configurations.

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:11.020
After installing Ansible, you must create
several text files that it can use.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:13.940
Playbooks are the ‘blueprint’ of automation
tasks.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:18.780
They outline the logic and actions of the
tasks that Ansible should do, and these playbooks

00:09:18.780 --> 00:09:21.240
are written in YAML.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:26.020
Then you’ll also need inventory files which
list the devices that will be managed by Ansible,

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:28.500
as well as their characteristics.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:34.500
For example, their device role such as access
switch, core switch, WAN router, firewall

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:38.120
etc can be listed as a characteristic.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:43.470
These inventory files can be written in multiple
formats, such as INI or YAML.

00:09:43.470 --> 00:09:48.850
You also need templates, which as you saw
earlier represent a device configuration file,

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:53.900
but specific values for variables are not
provided, for example the host name and IP

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:54.900
addresses.

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:58.550
These templates are written in a format called
Jinja2.

00:09:58.550 --> 00:10:01.200
And finally you’ll need variable files.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:05.340
They list variables and their values, as you
also saw earlier.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:10.440
These values are substituted into the templates
to create complete configuration files, and

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.430
these files are written in YAML.

00:10:12.430 --> 00:10:16.560
Let’s look at a diagram to visualize how
this works.

00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:22.680
So, here we have our inventory, templates,
variables, and playbook.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:27.390
The inventory provides a list of devices,
the template files provide configuration templates

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:33.140
for the devices, and the variables provide
specific variables and their values.

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:37.630
These inputs are given to the playbook which
takes the necessary actions to push the config

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:38.890
to the managed devices.

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:41.880
Okay, that’s all for Ansible.

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:47.650
You should know that it is agentless, written
in Python, uses a push model, uses SSH to

00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:53.530
connect to devices, and uses YAML for its
necessary files.

00:10:53.530 --> 00:10:55.060
Next up, Puppet.

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:59.920
Puppet is a configuration management tool
written in the programming language Ruby.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:04.890
It is typically agent-based, which means that
specific software, a Puppet agent, must be

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:07.850
installed on the managed devices.

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:12.240
And not all Cisco devices support a Puppet
agent, which is a major reason that Ansible

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:15.570
is more popular for network device management.

00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:20.850
However it can be run agentless, in which
a proxy agent runs on an external host and

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:26.580
the proxy agent uses SSH to connect to the
managed devices and communicate with them.

00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:30.110
Note that in Puppet the server is called the
Puppet master.

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:35.410
And Puppet uses a pull model, so clients pull
configurations from the Puppet master instead

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:39.130
of the Puppet master pushing configurations
to them.

00:11:39.130 --> 00:11:44.110
And note that clients use TCP 8140 to communicate
with the Puppet master.

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:47.160
You probably should remember that port number.

00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:52.090
And instead of YAML, it uses a proprietary
language for its files.

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:56.580
Like Ansible it requires some different text
files on the Puppet master, for example a

00:11:56.580 --> 00:12:01.630
Manifest file defines the desired configuration
state of a network device.

00:12:01.630 --> 00:12:06.020
The Puppet master then uses this Manifest
to generate specific configurations for the

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:08.180
managed devices.

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:12.380
And just like Ansible, templates are used
too, in this case to help generate Manifests

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:13.850
for the devices.

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:17.280
Here’s a very simplified look at that.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:21.590
Note that some of the devices have a Puppet
agent installed which provides a REST API

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:25.000
to communicate with the device, but one doesn’t.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.540
Instead it will communicate via the external
agent.

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:33.130
In both cases, the network devices are able
to pull configurations from the Puppet master.

00:12:33.130 --> 00:12:35.770
Okay, that’s Puppet.

00:12:35.770 --> 00:12:40.610
Remember that it’s written in Ruby, is typically
agent-based, the server is called the Puppet

00:12:40.610 --> 00:12:48.010
master, it uses a pull model, clients use
TCP 8140 to communicate with the Puppet master,

00:12:48.010 --> 00:12:53.690
it uses a proprietary language for its files
instead of YAML, and uses Manifests to define

00:12:53.690 --> 00:12:56.980
the desired configuration state of devices.

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:01.020
Those are the main points you should know
about Puppet.

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.120
Finally let’s look at Chef.

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:07.020
Like Puppet, it is a configuration management
tool written in Ruby.

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:11.990
It is agent-based, so specific software, a
Chef agent, must be installed on the managed

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:13.670
devices.

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:17.650
And not all Cisco devices support a Chef agent,
in fact most don’t.

00:13:17.650 --> 00:13:21.880
So, this is the least popular of the three
choices.

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:25.070
Like Puppet, Chef also uses a Pull model.

00:13:25.070 --> 00:13:30.480
And the Chef server uses TCP port 10002 to
send configurations to clients.

00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:33.800
It uses various other ports, too, but you
should remember 10002.

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:40.410
And Chef’s files use a DSL, Domain-Specific
Language, which is based on Ruby.

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:44.130
So, what are some of those files used by Chef.

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:47.850
We have resources, which are like the ingredients
in a recipe.

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:51.550
They define configuration objects managed
by Chef.

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:56.820
A configuration object could be, for example,
a set of configuration commands.

00:13:56.820 --> 00:14:00.050
Then there are recipes, like the recipes in
a cookbook.

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:05.030
They outline the logic and actions of the
tasks performed on the resources.

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:10.010
And of course there are cookbooks too, sets
of related recipes grouped together.

00:14:10.010 --> 00:14:14.400
And finally run-lists, which are an ordered
list of recipes that are run to bring a device

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:18.370
to the desired configuration state.

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:23.060
And here’s a diagram from the Chef website
demonstrating the architecture.

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:28.040
Admins will do their work on a Chef workstation,
a computer they use to prepare cookbooks,

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:30.000
recipes, etc.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.110
Required information is stored on a Chef server,
and the managed devices, the Chef clients,

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:36.960
communicate with the Chef server.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:43.040
Notice that possible clients include servers,
storage devices, virtual platforms, public

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:45.610
clouds, and of course network devices.

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:50.320
As mentioned earlier, these tools weren’t
designed specifically for network devices,

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:52.560
and they can be used for various purposes.

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.080
So, that’s Chef.

00:14:55.080 --> 00:15:01.580
Remember that it is written in Ruby, is agent-based,
uses a pull model, uses TCP 10002 to send

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:08.620
configurations, and its files such as cookbooks
use a language based on Ruby.

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:11.610
And finally, here’s a chart comparing the
three.

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:15.580
Something I didn’t mention clearly is that
Puppet and Chef both communicate using HTTP,

00:15:15.580 --> 00:15:17.700
via their REST APIs.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:22.980
I recommend memorizing these basic characteristics
as shown in the chart, you may be tested on

00:15:22.980 --> 00:15:24.030
them.

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:28.060
Okay, here’s what we covered in this video.

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:32.720
I introduced configuration management tools
and what we use them for.

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:38.690
And then I introduced three that you should
know for the CCNA: Ansible, Puppet, and Chef.

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:42.560
We only covered some very basic characteristics
of each of them, but that’s all you need

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:44.510
to know for the CCNA.

00:15:44.510 --> 00:15:49.560
As you continue your studies you’ll probably
get some hands on experience with these tools,

00:15:49.560 --> 00:15:54.250
especially Ansible, but for now you just need
to know the basics.

00:15:54.250 --> 00:15:58.300
And make sure to watch until the end of the
quiz for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:02.360
Software’s ExSim, the best practice exams
for the CCNA.

00:16:02.360 --> 00:16:07.420
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:12.360
Which of the following configuration management
tools connects to devices using SSH?

00:16:12.360 --> 00:16:17.360
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:23.029
Okay, the answer is B, Ansible.

00:16:23.029 --> 00:16:28.080
Ansible is agentless, so the control node
simply connects to managed devices using SSH.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:33.690
Now, a Puppet external agent also connects
to devices using SSH, but standard Puppet

00:16:33.690 --> 00:16:37.730
architecture does not, so Ansible is definitely
the better answer here.

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:42.070
